Here is how these theorems and their proofs would be translated into ProofJSON format:

```
[
  {
    "type": "theorem",
    "name": "Theorem 1",
    "statement": "Suppose $f:\\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}$ is a continuous function such that $f'(x) > 0$ for all $x \\in \\mathbb{R}$. Then $f$ is strictly increasing.",
    "status": "proved",
    "proof": [
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "For any $a < b$ in $\\mathbb{R}$, there exists $c \\in (a, b)$ such that $f'(c) = \\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}$.",
        "deduced-from": ["Mean Value Theorem", {"result": "$f'(x)>0$ for all $x \\in \\mathbb{R}$"}]
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "$f(b) > f(a)$",
        "deduced-from": ["$f'(c) > 0$", "$f'(c) = \\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}$"]
      },
      {
        "type": "conclusion",
        "claim": "$f$ is strictly increasing."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "theorem",
    "name": "Theorem 2",
    "statement": "Suppose $f:\\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}$ is a continuous and strictly increasing function. Then $f$ is unbounded.",
    "status": "proved",
    "proof": [
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "For any given $M > 0$, there exists $x_M \\in \\mathbb{R}$ such that $f(x_M) > M$.",
        "deduced-from": ["$f$ is strictly increasing"]
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "$f$ is unbounded above.",
        "deduced-from": ["For any given $M > 0$, there exists $x_M \\in \\mathbb{R}$ such that $f(x_M) > M$"]
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "For any given $M < 0$, there exists $x_M \\in \\mathbb{R}$ such that $f(x_M) < M$.",
        "deduced-from": ["$f$ is strictly increasing"]
      },
      {
        "type": "assertion",
        "claim": "$f$ is unbounded below.",
        "deduced-from": ["For any given $M < 0$, there exists $x_M \\in \\mathbb{R}$ such that $f(x_M) < M$"]
      },
      {
        "type": "conclusion",
        "claim": "$f$ is unbounded."
      }
    ]
  }
]
```

Note: The type "conclusion" is not clearly defined in your ProofJSON schema, but I used it here as a logical final step to mark the end of the proof. If this is not appropriate, you might need to modify the JSON accordingly.

